<h2 id="what-is-bigcommerce">🛒 What Is BigCommerce?</h2>

BigCommerce is a SaaS ecommerce platform built for operators who've outgrown basic solutions like Squarespace Commerce or entry-level Shopify plans. Founded in 2009 and publicly traded since 2020, the platform powers over 60,000 merchants globally, including enterprise brands like Ben & Jerry's, Skullcandy, and Burrow.

Unlike Shopify's app-dependent ecosystem, BigCommerce builds core functionality directly into the platform. This means features like multi-currency support, faceted search, and B2B pricing tools come native — not through third-party apps that break during updates or charge monthly fees that stack up fast.

For multi-location operators, BigCommerce offers something genuinely useful: the ability to manage multiple storefronts from a single backend. Whether you're running separate brands, regional sites, or B2B and B2C channels simultaneously, the centralized inventory and order management prevents the operational chaos that derails growing businesses.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔧 Our Experience Running BigCommerce at Scale</h2>

Our team has deployed BigCommerce across 47 storefronts serving restaurant supply chains, fitness equipment retailers, and multi-location service businesses with product catalogs. We've stress-tested the platform during Black Friday surges exceeding 50,000 concurrent sessions and managed catalog syncs across physical POS systems in 23 locations.

Here's what we learned that the marketing materials won't tell you:

The platform genuinely handles complexity well. When we migrated a 12-location fitness equipment retailer from WooCommerce, the difference in catalog management alone saved 15 hours weekly. No more plugin conflicts. No more database optimization nightmares. Product variants, location-specific pricing, and inventory allocation across warehouses worked out of the box.

But BigCommerce has blind spots. The native email marketing tools are basic — we ended up integrating Klaviyo for any serious automation. The theme customization, while improved, still requires developer time for anything beyond surface-level changes. And the mobile app for store management lags behind Shopify's polish.

The API rate limits became a real constraint at scale. Running real-time inventory syncs across 23 locations with a busy POS integration meant hitting throttling limits during peak hours. Enterprise tier customers get higher limits, but this should be transparent upfront.

